d. New permits to purchase B-category firearms issued only remotely (by post or electronic communication). \n| Ministry of Interior Explanatory Note No. MV- 49249-2/OBP-2020<ref>https://www.mvcr.cz/soubor/zajistovani-spravnich-cinnosti-v-oblasti-zbrani-v-dobe-nouzoveho-stavu.aspx</ref>\n|-\n| Criminal sanctions\n| COVID-19 added to list of diseases the willful spreading of which constitutes a felony. \n| 13 March 2020\n|\n| '''Up to 10 years imprisonment in case of criminal negligence.'''\n|Government Resolution No. 210/2020 Coll.<ref name=\"criminal sanctions\">https://www.vlada.cz/assets/media-centrum/aktualne/DOC130320-130320_210.pdf</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=8 style=\"text-align:center;\" | '''Healthcare provision support measures'''\n| {{No|'''Drive-through testing'''}}\n| 14 March 2020\n|\n| \"Drive-through\" tents set up in front of designated hospitals around the country. Patients don't need to leave their cars in order to be tested.\n\nTesting is free for people with prescriptions by the health authorities. Prescriptions are granted remotely (phone and email) based on symptoms and travel history. People lacking prescriptions may pay for their own tests. Prices vary depending on the hospital from CZK 1,300 to CZK 3,000 (\u20ac50 to \u20ac120). Some drive-through locations do not offer paid testing due to capacity limitations (i.e. they test only those with a prescription).\n|<ref>[https://www.blesk.cz/clanek/zpravy-koronavirus/637593/zmatek-v-testovani-na-nakazu-covid-19-vysetreni-si-muzete-zaplatit-v-peti-laboratorich.html Koronavirus: Laborato\u0159e, kter\u00e9 mohou testovat a kde si m\u016f\u017eete test zaplatit | Blesk.cz<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\" | '''COVID-19-only hospitals'''\n| 15 March 2020\n|\n| Two hospitals, {{Interlanguage link|Na Homolce Hospital|cs|Nemocnice Na Homolce}} in the capital and largest city of Prague, {{Interlanguage link|St. Anna University Hospital|cs|Fakultn\u00ed nemocnice u sv. Anny v Brn\u011b}} in the second largest city of Brno, were designated to deal with COVID-19 only. Both cities have several other hospitals to take up the caseload of other conditions.\n\nMilitary [[Biosafety level|BSL-4 reserve hospital]] at Biological Defense Center in [[T\u011bchon\u00edn]] put into a state of readiness.\n| {{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n|-\n| 28 March 2020\n|\n| After COVID-19 infection spread in at least seven retirement homes, several hundred beds were set aside for quarantine and treatment of elderly with mild symptoms at:\n* Na Bulovce hospital in Prague\n* Na Franti\u0161ku hospital in Prague\n* Health resort at [[L\u00e1zn\u011b Tou\u0161e\u0148]]\n* Non-emergency section of Military BSL-4 reserve hospital at Biological Defense Center in T\u011bchon\u00edn\n| Ministry of Health decision<ref>https://www.irozhlas.cz/zpravy-domov/domovy-pro-seniory-vyhrazena-luzka-v-nemocnicich-techonin-seniori-karantena-adam_2003281300_vtk</ref>\n|-\n| {{No|'''Medicine students' work duty'''}}\n| 15 March 2020\n| From 16 March until the end of State of Emergency\n| 5th and 6th-year students of General Medicine compelled to work duty, actual work subject to later call-up.\n\nLast-year students of nursing, paramedics, and several other related fields compelled to work duty, actual work subject to later call-up.\n| Government Resolution No. 220/2020 Coll.<ref>https://apps.odok.cz/attachment/-/down/IHOABMRE46CG</ref>\n|-\n| Healthcare workers' vacation ban\n| 23 March 2020\n| From 24 March until the end of State of Emergency\n| Healthcare workers banned from taking a vacation (time-off). \n| Government Resolution No. 278/2000 Coll.<ref name=\"23 March Resolutions\" />\n|-\n| '''Remdesivir provisional approval'''\n| 17 March 2020\n| From 17 March for a period of 9 months\n| [[Remdesivir]], originally developed by [[Gilead Sciences]] for [[ebola]] treatment, was approved for experimental use for COVID19 patients in serious condition.\n| Ministry of Health Decision No. MZDR 12059/2020-3/OLZP<ref>https://www.mzcr.cz/Soubor.ashx?souborID=40603&typ=application/pdf&nazev=Opat%C5%99en%C3%AD%20-%20LP%20Remdesivir.pdf</ref>\n|-\n| '''Plaquenil prescription restrictions'''\n| 23 March 2020\n| From 23 March 8 PM onwards (indefinitely)\n| [[Hydroxychloroquine]], sold under the brand name Plaquenil among others, is a medication used for the prevention and treatment of certain types of malaria. Plaquenil showed promise in some COVID-19 trials. Only doctors with selected specializations can prescribe it under the measure.\n| Ministry of Health Protection Measure No. MZDR 12756/2020-2/MIN/KAN<ref>https://www.mzcr.cz/Soubor.ashx?souborID=40681&typ=application/pdf&nazev=Mimo%C5%99%C3%A1dn%C3%A9%20opat%C5%99en%C3%AD%20-%20p%C5%99edepisov%C3%A1n%C3%AD%20l%C3%A9%C4%8Div%C3%A9ho%20p%C5%99%C3%ADpravku%20Plaquenil%2023.%203.%202020.pdf</ref> (until 3 April)\n\nMinistry of Health Protection Measure No. MZDR 12756/2020-3/MIN/KAN<ref>https://www.mzcr.cz/Soubor.ashx?souborID=40852&typ=application/pdf&nazev=Mimo%C5%99%C3%A1dn%C3%A9%20opat%C5%99en%C3%AD%20-%20p%C5%99edepisov%C3%A1n%C3%AD%20l%C3%A9%C4%8Div%C3%A9ho%20p%C5%99%C3%ADpravku%20Plaquenil.pdf</ref> (after 3 April)\n|-\n| Hospitalized patients' information database\n| 24 March 2020\n| From 24 March onwards (indefinitely)\n| Central database about COVID-19 hospitalized patients. Hospital providers ordered to:\n* insert data about the state of hospitalized COVID-19 patients daily\n* insert data about every new patient that gets either to serious condition, requires ventilator or ECMO within one hour\n* insert data about every patient whose state changes as regards serious condition, use of ventilator or ECMO within one hour\n| Ministry of Health Protection Measure No. MZDR 12996/2020-1/MIN/KAN<ref>https://www.mzcr.cz/Soubor.ashx?souborID=40693&typ=application/pdf&nazev=Mimo%C5%99%C3%A1dn%C3%A9%20opat%C5%99en%C3%AD%20-%20z%C3%A1znam%20o%20hospitalizovan%C3%A9m%20pozitivn%C3%ADm%20n%C3%A1lezu%20v%20ISIN.pdf</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Interpersonal solidarity==\n[[File:Ochrann\u00e1 rou\u0161ka, n\u00e1vod.webm|right|thumb|Demonstration of making facemasks without sewing]]\n\nThe COVID-19 pandemic in the Czech Republic has created a wave of solidarity in a variety of areas, including:\n* Due to the lack of protective face-masks, volunteers sewed masks for other people and also shared instruction videos online.<ref>https://ct24.ceskatelevize.cz/domaci/3063778-jak-si-vyrobit-nouzovou-rousku-bez-siti-socialni-site-radi-kus-latky-ministerstvo-i</ref>\n* Programs were launched to help the most vulnerable group -and seniors, on a non-commercial basis, by buying food and medicines.<ref>https://zlinsky.denik.cz/zpravy_region/pomoc-nejohrozenejsim-seniorum-privezou-nakupy-az-domu-20200318.html</ref>\n* On Monday, March 23, [[Czech Television|Czech National Television]] launched a temporary new television channel \u010cT3, which is to bring practical advice, news and a selection of \u010cT's classic programs from the archive for older people.<ref>https://www.ceskatelevize.cz/porady/10000000408-naladte-se-na-ct3/</ref>\n* The Vietnamese community in the [[\u00dast\u00ed nad Labem]] region raised CZK 140,000 for a donation of a ventilator to a hospital in \u00dast\u00ed nad Labem<ref>https://ustecky.denik.cz/zpravy_region/vietnamska-komunita-se-slozila-na-plicni-ventilatory-pro-usteckou-nemocnici-20200323.html</ref>\n* Due to the closure of Czech schools, Czech National Television launched an educational program for home education. The program \"U\u010d\u00edTelka\" is focusing on teaching first-grade pupils. The program \"Odpoledka\" on teaching second-grade pupils and program \"\u0160kola doma\" for ninth grade pupils preparing them for entrance exams to secondary schools.<ref>https://www.novinky.cz/domaci/clanek/ceska-televize-zacina-ucit-deti-zakladnich-skol-40316814</ref>\n*Czech manufacturer of 3D printers [[Prusa Research]] contributed to the \"free use project\" of shared [[Bicycle|bicycles]] company [[Rekola]] to enable access to transport with a lower risk of virus transmission than public transport.<ref>https://josefprusa.cz/prusa-research-a-boj-s-koronavirem-jak-je-dulezite-byt-pripraven/</ref> Prusa Research also designed, produced and distributed protective face shields for medical professionals.<ref>https://josefprusa.cz/od-navrhu-k-hromadnemu-3d-tisku-zdravotnickych-stitu-behem-tri-dnu/</ref>\n*The \u017duf\u00e1nek family distillery from [[Bor\u0161ice]] will produce and distribute for free disinfectant gels without the necessary permit from the health and agriculture department.<ref>https://zpravy.aktualne.cz/ekonomika/zufanek-dezinfekce/r~84235f126d0611ea80e60cc47ab5f122/</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Let\u00e1k_MZCR_Coronavirus_A5.pdf|Information flyer from the Ministry of Health sent to every house address \nFile:Usnesen\u00ed vl\u00e1dy k vyhl\u00e1\u0161en\u00ed nouzov\u00e9ho stavu.pdf|Government Resolution on Declaration of Emergency\nFile:COVID-19_Czech_Government_SMS_notification_about_shop_shutdown.jpg|SMS notification of the closure of shops\nFile:Celetn\u00e1 ulice bez turist\u016f 2020 03 203.jpg|Prague, Celetn\u00e1 ulice, without tourists(March 2020)\nFile:Starom\u011bstsk\u00fd orloj bez turist\u016f 2020 03 23.jpg|Prague, Astronomical clock, without spectators (March 2020)\nFile:V\u00e1clavsk\u00e9 n\u00e1m\u011bst\u00ed bez turist\u016f 2020 03 23.jpg|thumb|Prague, Wenceslas Square, without tourists (March 2020)\nFile:Praha Flora karant\u00e9na b\u0159ezen 2020.jpg|Prague, Flora shopping centre (March 2020)\nFile:No entry to driver's area in Brno city transport due to COVID-19 (detail).jpg|Brno, forbidden to enter front section of local bus. (March 2020)\n\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Healthcare in the Czech Republic]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://onemocneni-aktualne.mzcr.cz/covid-19/ Actual Situation Dashboard Ministry of healthcare]\n* [https://www.datawrapper.de/_/Sgf7v/ Epidemic curve from countries including the Czech Republic]\n* [https://covid-19-cz.chcepe.now.sh/ Interactive map of COVID-19 situation in the Czech Republic]\n* [https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6 Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases] and [https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19 historical data] by [[Johns Hopkins University]]\n* [https://theenewstimes.com/corona-virus-live-statistics/ Live Statistics of Corona-virus on the World Map]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable standard floatleft\" style=\"text-align:left;margin-top: 12px;\"\n|+\n!Information from the Ministry of Health of the Czech Republic - COVID-19\n|-\n|[https://koronavirus.mzcr.cz/seznam-odberovych-center/ Hospitals with COVID-19 testfacility - Blue is with self-pay testfacility]\n|-\n|[https://koronavirus.mzcr.cz/seznam-laboratori/ List of laboratories testing on COVID-19 in Czech Republic]\n|-\n|[https://koronavirus.mzcr.cz/en/ Important-phone-numbers and links// Emergency contact numbers]\n|-\n! Most services are available 24h and seven days a week\n|}\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in Europe|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 in the Czech Republic|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Cimmerian praetor", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWeek 14 (30 March \u2014 5 April)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_Czech_Republic"}
{"title_page": "Disappearance of Don Lewis", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Disappearance of Don Lewis\n| image = Don Lewis disappearance portrait.jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption =\n| birth_name = Jack Donald Lewis\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1938|4|30}}\n| birth_place =[[Dade City, Florida|Dade City]], [[Florida]], U.S.\n| other_names = Bob Martinez<ref name=\"Charley\">{{cite web|url=http://charleyproject.org/case/jack-donald-lewis|title=Jack Donald Lewis \u2013 The Charley Project|accessdate=April 1, 2020|date=September 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927192040/http://charleyproject.org/case/jack-donald-lewis|archive-date=September 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| death_date = August 19, 2002 ([[legal death]])\n| disappeared_date = {{Disappeared date and age|1997|8|18|1938|4|30}}\n| disappeared_place =[[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], Florida, U.S.\n| disappeared_status = {{Missing for|1997|8|18}}\n| spouse             = {{Plainlist|\n* Gladys Lewis Cross<br />({{abbr|div.|divorce}} 1990)\n* {{marriage|[[Carole Baskin]]|1991|2002|end={{abbr|legal d.|legal death}}}}}}\n| children           = 4\n}}\n\n'''Jack Donald Lewis''' (April 30, 1938 \u2013 {{abbr|legal d.|legal death}} August 19, 2002) disappeared on August 18, 1997, after leaving his home in [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], [[Florida]], United States.<ref name=\"WTSP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/extras/disappearance-on-easy-street/67-396338130|title=Disappearance on Easy Street|website=WTSP|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The investigation into his disappearance has stretched from Lewis' [[Big Cat Rescue]] sanctuary in Tampa, co-owned by his second wife [[Carole Baskin]], to land owned by Lewis in [[Costa Rica]]. No evidence of Lewis being killed has surfaced, but investigators believe that it is unlikely that he disappeared on his own. Lewis was declared [[legal death|legally dead]] in 2002. As of 2020, the case is still open. Lewis' disappearance was covered in 2020 crime documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', which focused on a feud between Baskin and private zoo owner [[Joe Exotic]].\n\n==Background==\nDon Lewis was a native of [[Dade City, Florida|Dade City]], [[Florida]], United States.<ref name=\"People\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/too-purrfect-vol-50-no-21/|title=Too Purrfect|date=December 7, 1998|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|first=Pam |last=Lambert|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329014604/https://people.com/archive/too-purrfect-vol-50-no-21/|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Lewis was a self-made millionaire by 1981 through the [[real estate]] and [[used car]]s businesses.<ref name=\"People\"/> By that time, Lewis was married to his first wife Gladys Lewis Cross<ref name=\"Kiro\">{{Cite news |first=Crystal |last=Bonvillian |url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/trending/tiger-king-sheriff-seeking-leads-1997-disappearance-carole-baskins-2nd-husband/FCSINAFMEZD7TD6B64DBHL6GZA/|title='Tiger King': Sheriff seeking leads in 1997 disappearance of Carole Baskin's 2nd husband|website=[[KIRO-TV|KIRO 7]]|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> and had three daughters and an adopted son.<ref name=\"People\"/> That year, Lewis first met [[Carole Baskin]] on Nebraska Avenue in Tampa when she was nineteen years old.<ref name=\"Intel\">{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/09/joe-exotic-and-his-american-animals.html|title= Joe Exotic bred lions, tigers, and ligers at his roadside zoo. He was a modern Barnum who found an equally extraordinary nemesis.|first=Robert |last=Moor|date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[New York (magazine)|Intelligencer]]}}</ref><ref name=\"TheSecret\">{{Cite episode|title=The Secret|series=[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]|season=1|number=3|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Baskin and Lewis engaged in an affair while both were still married.<ref name=\"TheSecret\"/> Baskin became one of Lewis' many girlfriends and she substantially grew his wealth by helping him buy and sell real estate in 1984.<ref name=\"People\"/> The couple divorced each of their spouses and married in 1991.<ref name=\"DBeast\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/joe-exotic-built-a-wild-animal-kingdom-he-was-the-most-dangerous-predator-of-them-all|title=Joe Exotic Built a Wild Animal Kingdom. He Was the Most Dangerous Predator of Them All.|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=June 22, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|first=Sean |last=Williams}}</ref> In 1992, Lewis and Baskin co-founded Wildlife on Easy Street (now called [[Big Cat Rescue]]), a [[big cat]]s [[animal sanctuary]] in Tampa. Lewis and Baskin were skeptical of every employee they hired with high expectations of loyalty.<ref name=\"Time\">{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5813268/tiger-king-carole-baskin-don-lewis-case/|title=<nowiki>'Everyone Had a Different Story.'</nowiki> ''Tiger King'' Popularity Leads Sheriff to Reopen the Case of Don Lewis's Disappearance|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020|author=Megan McCluskey|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402152441/https://time.com/5813268/tiger-king-carole-baskin-don-lewis-case/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Baskin and the 2020 crime documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', Lewis would take monthly flights to [[Costa Rica]] to deal with his [[Sexual addiction|sex addiction]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxygen.com/crime-news/what-happened-to-carole-baskins-ex-husband-don-lewis-from-tiger-king|title=What Happened To Carole Baskin's Former Husband, Who Vanished In 1997?|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]]|first=Gina |last=Tron}}</ref><ref name=\"Bible\">{{Cite web|url=https://brobible.com/culture/article/carole-baskin-boyfriend-restraining-order/|title=Carole Baskin's Boyfriend After Her Husband Disappeared Also Filed For A Chilling Restraining Order Against Her|first=Douglas |last=Charles|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=BroBible}}</ref> Lewis told family members and friends that he was planning to eventually move to Costa Rica.<ref name=\"People\"/> In early 1997, Lewis began transferring ownership of his properties in Florida to a Costa Rican company he controlled.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> In July 1997, Lewis filed a [[restraining order]] against Baskin, claiming that Baskin had threatened to kill him; the restraining order was rejected.<ref name=DonLewisMetro>{{Cite news |title=Tiger King: Who is Carole Baskin's first husband Jack 'Don' Lewis and when did he disappear? |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |website=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326151850/https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |archive-date=March 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lewis continued to live with Baskin afterwards.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> Lewis told Baskin multiple times that he wanted a [[divorce]], but she did not think he was ever serious.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> In the days leading up to his disappearance, Lewis bought a plane ticket to Costa Rica and was loading equipment on a truck destined for [[Miami]], Florida.<ref name=\"Tampa2005\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tampabay.com/archive/1998/08/23/mysterious-millionaire-still-missing/|title=Mysterious millionaire still missing|date=September 13, 2005|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[Tampa Bay Times]]|first=David |last=Karp}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\n[[File:Pilot Country Airport Gateway.jpg|thumb|left|Lewis' van was found at the Pilot Country Airport (pictured in 2016).<ref name=\"WTSP\"/>]]\nLewis disappeared on August 18, 1997, at around 6:00 a.m.<ref name=\"Charley\"/><ref name=\"WTSP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/extras/disappearance-on-easy-street/67-396338130|title=Disappearance on Easy Street|website=WTSP|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> On August 20, 1997, Lewis' white 1989 Dodge van was found at the Pilot Country Airport in Springhill, Florida, {{convert|40|mile|km}} away from the sanctuary.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/><ref name=\"People\"/> At the time of his disappearance, Lewis was known to own several planes and would fly them even though his [[private pilot licence]] was suspended.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> The keys to the van were found on the floorboard and the van had been parked for a couple of days.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> No evidence was found within the van.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> The [[Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office (Florida)|Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office]] \"found no sign of foul play\" at the Big Cat Rescue sanctuary and visited [[Bagaces]], Costa Rica, where Lewis owned a {{convert|200|acre|ha|abbr=off|adj=on}} park, as part of their investigation.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/><ref name=\"People\"/><ref name=\"Poly\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/tiger-king-carole-baskin-don-lewis.html|title='Tiger King': What Happened to Carole Baskin's Husband, Don Lewis?|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[The New York Times]]|first=Audra D. S. |last=Burch}}</ref> The investigation in Costa Rica lasted five days.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> In Costa Rica, investigators found indications that Lewis engaged in extramarital affairs and illegal business practices.<ref name=\"People\"/> Investigators also found that two of Lewis' [[ocelot]]s had recently been shipped out, but their whereabouts were not found.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> None of Lewis' [[credit card]]s have been used since his disappearance.<ref name=\"People\"/>\n\nLewis left behind holdings estimated at more than [[United States dollar|$]]5 million, leading to a legal dispute between Baskin and Lewis' children.<ref name=\"People\"/> Lewis was [[Legal death|declared legally dead]] in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Rosy|last=Cordero|url=https://ew.com/tv/tiger-king-carole-baskin-slams-netflix-documentary/|title='Tiger King' subject Carole Baskin slams Netflix doc, calls it 'salacious and sensational'|website=[[EW.com|Entertainment Weekly]]|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> Most of Lewis' estate was left to Baskin.<ref name=DonLewisMetro /> In 2004, Baskin refused to take a [[polygraph]] related to the investigation, as advised by her attorney.<ref name=\"Tampa2005\"/> Lewis' children have volunteered to take polygraphs.<ref name=\"Charley\"/><ref name=\"Tampa2005\"/> By 2005, authorities leaned away from the theory that Lewis disappeared on his own.<ref name=\"Tampa2005\"/> Hillsborough County Sergeant John Marsicano stated that, \"from an investigative standpoint\", it did not seem like Lewis ran off on his own.<ref name=\"Tampa2005\"/> No one has ever been arrested or charged with a crime in relation to the case.<ref name=\"Time\"/>\n\nIn 2020, the ''Tiger King'' series became popular as many people stayed at home due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]]. Using the popularity of ''Tiger King'', Hillsborough County Sheriff Chad Chronister appealed to the public for legitimate leads or evidence.<ref name=TampaSheriff>{{cite news|title=Hillsborough sheriff says tips are coming in 'Tiger King' missing millionaire case |first=Christopher |last=Spata |url=https://www.tampabay.com/news/crime/2020/03/31/hillsborough-sheriff-says-tips-are-coming-in-tiger-king-missing-millionaire-case/ |website=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Since the release of the series, the Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office has received six [[Tip (law enforcement)|tip]]s a day related to the disappearance.<ref name=\"Poly\"/> Chronister expressed his belief that a former employee of  Wildlife on Easy Street that had a sour relationship with Lewis or Baskin will step forward with evidence.<ref name=\"Time\"/> Chronister reiterated that his department does not \"have any type of evidence, not one piece, that suggests that [Lewis] was killed\" or that a crime was even committed.<ref name=\"Time\"/><ref name=\"Poly\"/> Chronister also stated his opinion that ''Tiger King'' was [[Spin (propaganda)|spun]] for entertainment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/tiger-king-updates.html|title=What Happened After 'Tiger King'|website=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020|author1=Alan Yuhas|author2=Maria Cramer|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402151248/https://www.nytimes.com/article/tiger-king-updates.html|archive-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The case is still open as of 2020.<ref name=\"CBS\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/police-ask-for-new-leads-in-disappearance-of-don-lewis-husband-of-tiger-king-star-carole-baskin/|title=Police ask for new leads in disappearance of Don Lewis, husband of \"Tiger King\" star Carole Baskin|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[CBS News]]|first=Danielle|last=Garrand}}</ref>\n\n==Unofficial theories==\n[[File:Tiger at Big Cat Rescue.jpg|thumb|right|An unsubstantiated theory claims that Lewis' wife [[Carole Baskin]] fed him to tigers at their animal sanctuary (pictured in 2012).]]\nIn December 1998, Pam Lambert of ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' wrote that there was \"a wealth of suspects and scenarios, but little precious evidence\".<ref name=\"People\"/> The third episode of ''Tiger King'', \"The Secret\", covered multiple theories surrounding Lewis' disappearance.<ref name=\"Kiro\"/> Lewis' children have pushed a theory that Baskin fed Lewis to the tigers, and have criticized investigators for not running a [[Genetic testing|DNA test]] on a [[meat grinder]] at the sanctuary.<ref name=\"People\"/> However, the meat grinder was removed from the sanctuary weeks before Lewis' disappearance.<ref name=\"Time\"/> Baskin reacted to the allegations saying that there would be human bones as remains if the tigers would have eaten Lewis.<ref name=\"People\"/> Baskin expressed her disappointment about the theories to Lambert, saying \"Can you imagine having people think you killed your husband or wife and not being able to prove otherwise? Without a body, there is nothing I can do to clear my name.\"<ref name=\"People\"/>\n\nBaskin has a long-running feud with private zoo owner [[Joe Exotic]].<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Not Your Average Joe|series=[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]|season=1|number=1|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Exotic has promoted an unsubstantiated theory that Baskin was involved in the disappearance of Lewis.<ref name=\"CBS\"/> Exotic created a music video entitled \"Here Kitty Kitty\" that featured a Baskin-lookalike feeding raw meat to tigers.<ref name=\"Kiro\"/> Exotic has promoted an alternative theory that Lewis is buried in a [[septic tank]] at the property,<ref name=\"StyleCaster\">{{Cite web|url=https://stylecaster.com/what-happened-to-carole-baskin-husband-tiger-king-netflix/|title=5 'Tiger King' Theories That Explain What Happened to Carole Baskin\u2019s Missing Husband|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020|author=Jason Pham|website=[[SheKnows Media|StyleCaster]]}}</ref> but the septic tank was not installed until years after Lewis' disappearance.<ref name=\"Time\"/> Other theories covered by ''Tiger King'' include Lewis flying to Costa Rica and living his life under a new identity or that on his way to Costa Rica, his plane crashed.<ref name=\"StyleCaster\"/> After ''Tiger King'' was released, several [[Internet meme]]s targeted Baskin for her speculated involvement in Lewis' disappearance.<ref name=\"Kiro\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Tiger King}}\n\n[[Category:1990s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:August 1997 crimes]]\n[[Category:August 1997 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Unsolved crimes in the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Dade City, Florida|Lewis, Don]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Disappearance of Don Lewis\n| image = Don Lewis disappearance portrait.jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption =\n| birth_name = Jack Donald Lewis\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1938|4|30}}\n| birth_place =[[Dade City, Florida|Dade City]], [[Florida]], U.S.\n| other_names = Bob Martinez<ref name=\"Charley\">{{cite web|url=http://charleyproject.org/case/jack-donald-lewis|title=Jack Donald Lewis \u2013 The Charley Project|accessdate=April 1, 2020|date=September 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927192040/http://charleyproject.org/case/jack-donald-lewis|archive-date=September 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| death_date = August 18, 2002 ([[legal death]])\n| disappeared_date = {{Disappeared date and age|1997|8|18|1938|4|30}}\n| disappeared_place =[[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], Florida, U.S.\n| disappeared_status = {{Missing for|1997|8|18}}\n| spouse             = {{Plainlist|\n* Gladys Lewis Cross<br />({{abbr|div.|divorce}} 1990)\n* {{marriage|[[Carole Baskin]]|1991|2002|end={{abbr|legal d.|legal death}}}}}}\n| children           = 4\n}}\n\n'''Jack Donald Lewis''' (April 30, 1938 \u2013 {{abbr|legal d.|legal death}} August 18, 2002) disappeared on August 18, 1997, after leaving his home in [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], [[Florida]], United States.<ref name=\"WTSP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/extras/disappearance-on-easy-street/67-396338130|title=Disappearance on Easy Street|website=WTSP|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The investigation into his disappearance has stretched from Lewis' [[Big Cat Rescue]] sanctuary in Tampa, co-owned by his second wife [[Carole Baskin]], to land owned by Lewis in [[Costa Rica]]. No evidence of Lewis being killed has surfaced, but investigators believe that it is unlikely that he disappeared on his own. Lewis was declared [[legal death|legally dead]] in 2002. As of 2020, the case is still open. Lewis' disappearance was covered in 2020 crime documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', which focused on a feud between Baskin and private zoo owner [[Joe Exotic]].\n\n==Background==\nDon Lewis was a native of [[Dade City, Florida|Dade City]], [[Florida]], United States.<ref name=\"People\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/too-purrfect-vol-50-no-21/|title=Too Purrfect|date=December 7, 1998|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|first=Pam |last=Lambert|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329014604/https://people.com/archive/too-purrfect-vol-50-no-21/|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Lewis was a self-made millionaire by 1981 through the [[real estate]] and [[used car]]s businesses.<ref name=\"People\"/> By that time, Lewis was married to his first wife Gladys Lewis Cross<ref name=\"Kiro\">{{Cite news |first=Crystal |last=Bonvillian |url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/trending/tiger-king-sheriff-seeking-leads-1997-disappearance-carole-baskins-2nd-husband/FCSINAFMEZD7TD6B64DBHL6GZA/|title='Tiger King': Sheriff seeking leads in 1997 disappearance of Carole Baskin's 2nd husband|website=[[KIRO-TV|KIRO 7]]|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> and had three daughters and an adopted son.<ref name=\"People\"/> That year, Lewis first met [[Carole Baskin]] on Nebraska Avenue in Tampa when she was nineteen years old.<ref name=\"Intel\">{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/09/joe-exotic-and-his-american-animals.html|title= Joe Exotic bred lions, tigers, and ligers at his roadside zoo. He was a modern Barnum who found an equally extraordinary nemesis.|first=Robert |last=Moor|date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[New York (magazine)|Intelligencer]]}}</ref><ref name=\"TheSecret\">{{Cite episode|title=The Secret|series=[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]|season=1|number=3|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Baskin and Lewis engaged in an affair while both were still married.<ref name=\"TheSecret\"/> Baskin became one of Lewis' many girlfriends and she substantially grew his wealth by helping him buy and sell real estate in 1984.<ref name=\"People\"/> The couple divorced each of their spouses and married in 1991.<ref name=\"DBeast\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/joe-exotic-built-a-wild-animal-kingdom-he-was-the-most-dangerous-predator-of-them-all|title=Joe Exotic Built a Wild Animal Kingdom. He Was the Most Dangerous Predator of Them All.|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=June 22, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|first=Sean |last=Williams}}</ref> In 1992, Lewis and Baskin co-founded Wildlife on Easy Street (now called [[Big Cat Rescue]]), a [[big cat]]s [[animal sanctuary]] in Tampa. Lewis and Baskin were skeptical of every employee they hired with high expectations of loyalty.<ref name=\"Time\">{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5813268/tiger-king-carole-baskin-don-lewis-case/|title=<nowiki>'Everyone Had a Different Story.'</nowiki> ''Tiger King'' Popularity Leads Sheriff to Reopen the Case of Don Lewis's Disappearance|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020|author=Megan McCluskey|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402152441/https://time.com/5813268/tiger-king-carole-baskin-don-lewis-case/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Baskin and the 2020 crime documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', Lewis would take monthly flights to [[Costa Rica]] to deal with his [[Sexual addiction|sex addiction]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxygen.com/crime-news/what-happened-to-carole-baskins-ex-husband-don-lewis-from-tiger-king|title=What Happened To Carole Baskin's Former Husband, Who Vanished In 1997?|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]]|first=Gina |last=Tron}}</ref><ref name=\"Bible\">{{Cite web|url=https://brobible.com/culture/article/carole-baskin-boyfriend-restraining-order/|title=Carole Baskin's Boyfriend After Her Husband Disappeared Also Filed For A Chilling Restraining Order Against Her|first=Douglas |last=Charles|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=BroBible}}</ref> Lewis told family members and friends that he was planning to eventually move to Costa Rica.<ref name=\"People\"/> In early 1997, Lewis began transferring ownership of his properties in Florida to a Costa Rican company he controlled.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> In July 1997, Lewis filed a [[restraining order]] against Baskin, claiming that Baskin had threatened to kill him; the restraining order was rejected.<ref name=DonLewisMetro>{{Cite news |title=Tiger King: Who is Carole Baskin's first husband Jack 'Don' Lewis and when did he disappear? |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |website=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326151850/https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |archive-date=March 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lewis continued to live with Baskin afterwards.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> Lewis told Baskin multiple times that he wanted a [[divorce]], but she did not think he was ever serious.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> In the days leading up to his disappearance, Lewis bought a plane ticket to Costa Rica and was loading equipment on a truck destined for [[Miami]], Florida.<ref name=\"Tampa2005\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tampabay.com/archive/1998/08/23/mysterious-millionaire-still-missing/|title=Mysterious millionaire still missing|date=September 13, 2005|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[Tampa Bay Times]]|first=David |last=Karp}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\n[[File:Pilot Country Airport Gateway.jpg|thumb|left|Lewis' van was found at the Pilot Country Airport (pictured in 2016).<ref name=\"WTSP\"/>]]\nLewis disappeared on August 18, 1997, at around 6:00 a.m.<ref name=\"Charley\"/><ref name=\"WTSP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/extras/disappearance-on-easy-street/67-396338130|title=Disappearance on Easy Street|website=WTSP|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> On August 20, 1997, Lewis' white 1989 Dodge van was found at the Pilot Country Airport in Springhill, Florida, {{convert|40|mile|km}} away from the sanctuary.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/><ref name=\"People\"/> At the time of his disappearance, Lewis was known to own several planes and would fly them even though his [[private pilot licence]] was suspended.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> The keys to the van were found on the floorboard and the van had been parked for a couple of days.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> No evidence was found within the van.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> The [[Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office (Florida)|Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office]] \"found no sign of foul play\" at the Big Cat Rescue sanctuary and visited [[Bagaces]], Costa Rica, where Lewis owned a {{convert|200|acre|ha|abbr=off|adj=on}} park, as part of their investigation.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/><ref name=\"People\"/><ref name=\"Poly\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/tiger-king-carole-baskin-don-lewis.html|title='Tiger King': What Happened to Carole Baskin's Husband, Don Lewis?|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[The New York Times]]|first=Audra D. S. |last=Burch}}</ref> The investigation in Costa Rica lasted five days.<ref name=\"Charley\"/> In Costa Rica, investigators found indications that Lewis engaged in extramarital affairs and illegal business practices.<ref name=\"People\"/> Investigators also found that two of Lewis' [[ocelot]]s had recently been shipped out, but their whereabouts were not found.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> None of Lewis' [[credit card]]s have been used since his disappearance.<ref name=\"People\"/>\n\nLewis left behind holdings estimated at more than [[United States dollar|$]]5 million, leading to a legal dispute between Baskin and Lewis' children.<ref name=\"People\"/> Lewis was [[Legal death|declared legally dead]] in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Rosy|last=Cordero|url=https://ew.com/tv/tiger-king-carole-baskin-slams-netflix-documentary/|title='Tiger King' subject Carole Baskin slams Netflix doc, calls it 'salacious and sensational'|website=[[EW.com|Entertainment Weekly]]|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> Most of Lewis' estate was left to Baskin.<ref name=DonLewisMetro /> In 2004, Baskin refused to take a [[polygraph]] related to the investigation, as advised by her attorney.<ref name=\"Tampa2005\"/> Lewis' children have volunteered to take polygraphs.<ref name=\"Charley\"/><ref name=\"Tampa2005\"/> By 2005, authorities leaned away from the theory that Lewis disappeared on his own.<ref name=\"Tampa2005\"/> Hillsborough County Sergeant John Marsicano stated that, \"from an investigative standpoint\", it did not seem like Lewis ran off on his own.<ref name=\"Tampa2005\"/> No one has ever been arrested or charged with a crime in relation to the case.<ref name=\"Time\"/>\n\nIn 2020, the ''Tiger King'' series became popular as many people stayed at home due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]]. Using the popularity of ''Tiger King'', Hillsborough County Sheriff Chad Chronister appealed to the public for legitimate leads or evidence.<ref name=TampaSheriff>{{cite news|title=Hillsborough sheriff says tips are coming in 'Tiger King' missing millionaire case |first=Christopher |last=Spata |url=https://www.tampabay.com/news/crime/2020/03/31/hillsborough-sheriff-says-tips-are-coming-in-tiger-king-missing-millionaire-case/ |website=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Since the release of the series, the Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office has received six [[Tip (law enforcement)|tip]]s a day related to the disappearance.<ref name=\"Poly\"/> Chronister expressed his belief that a former employee of  Wildlife on Easy Street that had a sour relationship with Lewis or Baskin will step forward with evidence.<ref name=\"Time\"/> Chronister reiterated that his department does not \"have any type of evidence, not one piece, that suggests that [Lewis] was killed\" or that a crime was even committed.<ref name=\"Time\"/><ref name=\"Poly\"/> Chronister also stated his opinion that ''Tiger King'' was [[Spin (propaganda)|spun]] for entertainment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/tiger-king-updates.html|title=What Happened After 'Tiger King'|website=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020|author1=Alan Yuhas|author2=Maria Cramer|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402151248/https://www.nytimes.com/article/tiger-king-updates.html|archive-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The case is still open as of 2020.<ref name=\"CBS\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/police-ask-for-new-leads-in-disappearance-of-don-lewis-husband-of-tiger-king-star-carole-baskin/|title=Police ask for new leads in disappearance of Don Lewis, husband of \"Tiger King\" star Carole Baskin|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[CBS News]]|first=Danielle|last=Garrand}}</ref>\n\n==Unofficial theories==\n[[File:Tiger at Big Cat Rescue.jpg|thumb|right|An unsubstantiated theory claims that Lewis' wife [[Carole Baskin]] fed him to tigers at their animal sanctuary (pictured in 2012).]]\nIn December 1998, Pam Lambert of ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' wrote that there was \"a wealth of suspects and scenarios, but little precious evidence\".<ref name=\"People\"/> The third episode of ''Tiger King'', \"The Secret\", covered multiple theories surrounding Lewis' disappearance.<ref name=\"Kiro\"/> Lewis' children have pushed a theory that Baskin fed Lewis to the tigers, and have criticized investigators for not running a [[Genetic testing|DNA test]] on a [[meat grinder]] at the sanctuary.<ref name=\"People\"/> However, the meat grinder was removed from the sanctuary weeks before Lewis' disappearance.<ref name=\"Time\"/> Baskin reacted to the allegations saying that there would be human bones as remains if the tigers would have eaten Lewis.<ref name=\"People\"/> Baskin expressed her disappointment about the theories to Lambert, saying \"Can you imagine having people think you killed your husband or wife and not being able to prove otherwise? Without a body, there is nothing I can do to clear my name.\"<ref name=\"People\"/>\n\nBaskin has a long-running feud with private zoo owner [[Joe Exotic]].<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Not Your Average Joe|series=[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]|season=1|number=1|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Exotic has promoted an unsubstantiated theory that Baskin was involved in the disappearance of Lewis.<ref name=\"CBS\"/> Exotic created a music video entitled \"Here Kitty Kitty\" that featured a Baskin-lookalike feeding raw meat to tigers.<ref name=\"Kiro\"/> Exotic has promoted an alternative theory that Lewis is buried in a [[septic tank]] at the property,<ref name=\"StyleCaster\">{{Cite web|url=https://stylecaster.com/what-happened-to-carole-baskin-husband-tiger-king-netflix/|title=5 'Tiger King' Theories That Explain What Happened to Carole Baskin\u2019s Missing Husband|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020|author=Jason Pham|website=[[SheKnows Media|StyleCaster]]}}</ref> but the septic tank was not installed until years after Lewis' disappearance.<ref name=\"Time\"/> Other theories covered by ''Tiger King'' include Lewis flying to Costa Rica and living his life under a new identity or that on his way to Costa Rica, his plane crashed.<ref name=\"StyleCaster\"/> After ''Tiger King'' was released, several [[Internet meme]]s targeted Baskin for her speculated involvement in Lewis' disappearance.<ref name=\"Kiro\"/>\n\n