{"title_page": "Sentul Barat MRT station", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox station\n| name = {{KLRT code2|SSP|16}}<br />Sentul Barat<br/>{{rint|my|rapidkl}}\n| logo = \n| logo_size = \n| type = ''Future [[Rapid Rail]] station''\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_caption = \n| address = [[Jalan Ipoh]], [[Sentul, KL|Sentul]], [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Malaysia]].\n| operator = [[Rapid Rail]]\n| line = {{rint|my|12}} {{KLRT lines|12|x}}\n| other = \n| platform = 1 [[island platform]]\n| tracks = 2\n| structure = Half-sunken\n| parking = Available\n| bicycle = \n| baggage_check = \n| passengers = \n| pass_year = \n| pass_percent = \n| pass_system = \n| opened = \n| opening = July 2022\n| rebuilt = \n| electrified = \n| ADA = \n| status = Under construction\n| code = {{KLRT code2|SSP|16}}\n| owned = [[MRT Corp]]\n| zone = \n| services = {{s-rail|title=Klang Valley MRT}}\n{{s-line|system=Klang Valley MRT|line=Sungai Buloh-Serdang-Putrajaya Line|previous=Jalan Ipoh|next=Titiwangsa}}\n| mpassengers = \n}}\nThe '''Sentul Barat MRT station''' ''(Working name: Sentul West)'' is a [[Rapid transit|mass rapid transit]] (MRT) station under construction that will serve the suburb of [[Sentul, KL|Sentul]] in [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Malaysia]]. It is one of the stations being built as part of the [[Klang Valley Mass Rapid Transit]] (KVMRT) project on the [[Sungai Buloh-Serdang-Putrajaya Line]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mymrt.com.my/en/ssp/project-info/route-map|title=MYMRT {{!}} MRT Corp - Official webpage for the Klang Valley My Rapid Transit.|website=www.mymrt.com.my|language=en|access-date=2017-05-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170627024608/http://mymrt.com.my/en/ssp/project-info/route-map|archivedate=2017-06-27}}</ref>. The station is located at [[Jalan Ipoh]] near the [[Kuala Lumpur Performing Arts Centre]] (KLPAC).\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mymrt.com.my Klang Valley Mass Rapid Transit website]\n* [http://www.mymrt.com.my/hawk-eye-view/ MRT Hawk-Eye View]\n\n{{Klang Valley train stations}}\n\n{{coord missing|Malaysia}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Kuala Lumpur]]\n[[Category:Rapid transit stations in Kuala Lumpur]]\n[[Category:Sungai Buloh-Serdang-Putrajaya Line]]\n\n{{Malaysia-rail-transport-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox station\n| name = {{KLRT code2|SSP|16}}<br />Sentul Barat<br/>{{rint|my|rapidkl}}\n| logo = \n| logo_size = \n| type = ''Future [[Rapid Rail]] station''\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_caption = \n| address = [[Jalan Ipoh]], [[Sentul, Kuala Lumpur|Sentul]], [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Malaysia]].\n| operator = [[Rapid Rail]]\n| line = {{rint|my|12}} {{KLRT lines|12|x}}\n| other = \n| platform = 1 [[island platform]]\n| tracks = 2\n| structure = Half-sunken\n| parking = Available\n| bicycle = \n| baggage_check = \n| passengers = \n| pass_year = \n| pass_percent = \n| pass_system = \n| opened = \n| opening = July 2022\n| rebuilt = \n| electrified = \n| ADA = \n| status = Under construction\n| code = {{KLRT code2|SSP|16}}\n| owned = [[MRT Corp]]\n| zone = \n| services = {{s-rail|title=Klang Valley MRT}}\n{{s-line|system=Klang Valley MRT|line=Sungai Buloh-Serdang-Putrajaya Line|previous=Jalan Ipoh|next=Titiwangsa}}\n| mpassengers = \n}}\nThe '''Sentul Barat MRT station''' ''(Working name: Sentul West)'' is a [[Rapid transit|mass rapid transit]] (MRT) station under construction that will serve the suburb of [[Sentul, Kuala Lumpur|Sentul]] in [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Malaysia]]. It is one of the stations being built as part of the [[Klang Valley Mass Rapid Transit]] (KVMRT) project on the [[Sungai Buloh-Serdang-Putrajaya Line]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mymrt.com.my/en/ssp/project-info/route-map|title=MYMRT {{!}} MRT Corp - Official webpage for the Klang Valley My Rapid Transit.|website=www.mymrt.com.my|language=en|access-date=2017-05-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170627024608/http://mymrt.com.my/en/ssp/project-info/route-map|archivedate=2017-06-27}}</ref>. The station is located on [[Jalan Ipoh]] between [[Viva Residency]] and the [[Kuala Lumpur Performing Arts Centre]] (KLPAC).\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mymrt.com.my Klang Valley Mass Rapid Transit website]\n* [http://www.mymrt.com.my/hawk-eye-view/ MRT Hawk-Eye View]\n\n{{Klang Valley train stations}}\n\n{{coord missing|Malaysia}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Kuala Lumpur]]\n[[Category:Rapid transit stations in Kuala Lumpur]]\n[[Category:Sungai Buloh-Serdang-Putrajaya Line]]\n\n{{Malaysia-rail-transport-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Thomstho", "label": "safe", "comment": "proofread", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sentul_Barat_MRT_station"}
{"title_page": "Gustavs Vanags", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Gustavs Vanags\n| image = Gustavs Vanags.jpg\n| image_size = 180px\n| alt = Head and a torso of a smiling bolding man in his fifties, dressed in a dinner suit\n| caption = <!--(not needed as image is straightforward portrait)-->\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1891|3|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = {{flagicon|Russia}}[[\u017dagar\u0117|\u017dagare parish]], [[Kovno Governorate]], [[Russian Empire]] (now in {{flagicon|Latvia}}[[Latvia]])\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1965|5|8|1891|3|10|df=y}}\n| death_place = {{flagicon|USSR}} [[Riga]], [[Latvian SSR]], USSR\n| nationality = [[Latvian]]\n| fields = [[Chemistry]] ([[Organic synthesis|organic]])\n| workplaces = {{Unbulleted list | [[University of Latvia]] |[[Riga Polytechnic Institute]]}}\n| alma_mater = [[University of Latvia]]\n| academic_advisors = [[Paul Walden]]\n| doctoral_students = {{ublist |[[Em\u012blija Gudriniece]] |[[J\u0101nis Polis]]}}\n| known_for = {{longitem|Contribution to diketone chemistry}}\n| awards = {{Unbulleted list | {{smaller|1959{{nbsp|2}}}}State Award of Latvian SSR | {{smaller|1961{{nbsp|2}}}}[[Order of the Red Banner of Labour]]}}\n}}\n'''Gustavs Vanags''' (10 March 1891 \u2014 8 May 1965) was a Latvian organic chemist,  full member of [[Latvian SSR Academy of Sciences|Latvian SSR Academy of Science]]. He was also one of the signers of the Memorandum of [[Latvian Central Council]] in 1944.\n\n== Biography ==\nGustavs Vanags was born in \"Rungas\" house of  the Schnicken (Sni\u0137eru) manor (now in [[Ukri parish]], [[Auce municipality]]). He received primary education in the [[Jelgava|Mitau]] Classic [[Gymnasium (school)|Gymnasium]], and in 1910 enrolled Riga Polytechnic Institute. During the First World War, he, among many, went in evacuation to the inner regions of Russian Empire; after returning from it in 1921, he completed his education in the new-founded University of Latvia and worked at the Faculty of Chemistry, raising to the position of the chair of the Department of organic chemistry. He received his [[habilitation]] in 1932.\n\nAfter Riga Polytechnic Institute was reestablished in 1958, G. Vanags moved to it, serving in the same position as the department chair until 1965. Simultaneously he also worked in the State Institute of Organic Synthesis, where he carried out his research in the chemistry of cyclic \u03b2-[[diketones]]. He was founder of Riga scholl of organic chemists specializing on \u03b2-diketones, which continues up to day (2020). Gustavs Vanags, along with his students, designed and synthesized several compounds of notable application in medicine, agriculture and chemical analysis (omefin, bindon,<ref>{{cite web|publisher=PubChem|url=https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Bindone|access-date=3 April 2020|title=Bindone}}</ref> nitroindandione,<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Acta Crystallographica]] B|year=1977|volume=B33|pages=3045-3049|title=The crystal and molecular structure of 2-nitro-1,3-indandione dihydrate. A hydronium nitronate|last1=Simonsen|first1=Ole|last2=Jacobsen|first2=Jens P.}}</ref> rhodenticide [[diphenadione]] or ratindan).\n\nGustavs Vanags died in a sudden death on May 8th, 1965, in Riga. He was buried in the [[Riga Forest Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lu.lv/zinas/t/6301/ |title=Izst\u0101de Gustavs Vanags un organisk\u0101 \u0137\u012bmija Latvij\u0101 |access-date=19 January 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926210338/http://www.lu.lv/zinas/t/6301/ |archivedate=26 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n== Commemoration ==\nLatvian Academy of Sciences named a biannual prize for advances in chemistry in Gustavs Vanags' name.\n\nA commemorative plaque with bas-relief of G. Vanags is installed in the hall of [[Riga Technical University|Riga Technical University Faculty of Chemistry]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.letonika.lv/groups/default.aspx?r=2&q=Latvija&id=967022&g=1 Article in Letonika encyclopedia]\u00a0\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110926210338/http://www.lu.lv/zinas/t/6301/ Exhibition \"Gustavs Vanags and organic chemistry in Latvia]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gudriniece, Emilija}}\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:Latvian chemists]]\n[[Category:Latvian inventors]]\n[[Category:Latvian academicians]]\n[[Category:Academicians of the Latvian SSR Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:University of Latvia alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Latvia faculty]]\n[[Category:Riga Technical University faculty]]\n[[Category:Riga Technical University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Zemgale]]\n[[Category:People from Kovno Governorate]]\n[[Category:People from Auce Municipality]]\n[[Category:20th-century chemists]]\n\n{{cat improve|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Gustavs Vanags\n| image = Gustavs Vanags.jpg\n| image_size = 180px\n| alt = Head and a torso of a smiling bolding man in his fifties, dressed in a dinner suit\n| caption = <!--(not needed as image is straightforward portrait)-->\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1891|3|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = {{flagicon|Russia}}[[\u017dagar\u0117|\u017dagare parish]], [[Kovno Governorate]], [[Russian Empire]] (now in {{flagicon|Latvia}}[[Latvia]])\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1965|5|8|1891|3|10|df=y}}\n| death_place = {{flagicon|USSR}} [[Riga]], [[Latvian SSR]], USSR\n| nationality = [[Latvian]]\n| fields = [[Chemistry]] ([[Organic synthesis|organic]])\n| workplaces = {{Unbulleted list | [[University of Latvia]] |[[Riga Polytechnic Institute]]}}\n| alma_mater = [[University of Latvia]]\n| academic_advisors = [[Paul Walden]]\n| doctoral_students = {{ublist |[[Em\u012blija Gudriniece]] |[[J\u0101nis Polis]]}}\n| known_for = {{longitem|Contribution to diketone chemistry}}\n| awards = {{Unbulleted list | {{smaller|1959{{nbsp|2}}}}State Award of Latvian SSR | {{smaller|1961{{nbsp|2}}}}[[Order of the Red Banner of Labour]]}}\n}}\n'''Gustavs Vanags''' (10 March 1891 \u2014 8 May 1965) was a Latvian organic chemist,  full member of [[Latvian SSR Academy of Sciences|Latvian SSR Academy of Science]]. He was also one of the signers of the Memorandum of [[Latvian Central Council]] in 1944.\n\n== Biography ==\nGustavs Vanags was born in \"Rungas\" house of  the Schnicken (Sni\u0137eru) manor (now in [[Ukri parish]], [[Auce municipality]]). He received primary education in the [[Jelgava|Mitau]] Classic [[Gymnasium (school)|Gymnasium]], and in 1910 enrolled Riga Polytechnic Institute. During the First World War, he, among many, went in evacuation to the inner regions of Russian Empire; after returning from it in 1921, he completed his education in the new-founded University of Latvia and worked at the Faculty of Chemistry, raising to the position of the chair of the Department of organic chemistry. He received his [[habilitation]] in 1932.\n\nAfter Riga Polytechnic Institute was reestablished in 1958, G. Vanags moved to it, serving in the same position as the department chair until 1965. Simultaneously he also worked in the State Institute of Organic Synthesis, where he carried out his research in the chemistry of cyclic \u03b2-[[diketones]]. He was founder of Riga scholl of organic chemists specializing on \u03b2-diketones, which continues up to day (2020). Gustavs Vanags, along with his students, designed and synthesized several compounds of notable application in medicine, agriculture and chemical analysis (omefin, bindon,<ref>{{cite web|publisher=PubChem|url=https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/Bindone|access-date=3 April 2020|title=Bindone}}</ref> nitroindandione,<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Acta Crystallographica]] B|year=1977|volume=B33|pages=3045-3049|title=The crystal and molecular structure of 2-nitro-1,3-indandione dihydrate. A hydronium nitronate|last1=Simonsen|first1=Ole|last2=Jacobsen|first2=Jens P.}}</ref> rhodenticide [[diphenadione]] or ratindan).\n\nGustavs Vanags died in a sudden death on May 8th, 1965, in Riga. He was buried in the [[Riga Forest Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lu.lv/zinas/t/6301/ |title=Izst\u0101de Gustavs Vanags un organisk\u0101 \u0137\u012bmija Latvij\u0101 |access-date=19 January 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926210338/http://www.lu.lv/zinas/t/6301/ |archivedate=26 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n== Commemoration ==\nLatvian Academy of Sciences named a biannual prize for advances in chemistry in Gustavs Vanags' name.\n\nA commemorative plaque with bas-relief of G. Vanags is installed in the hall of Riga Technical University Faculty of Chemistry.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.letonika.lv/groups/default.aspx?r=2&q=Latvija&id=967022&g=1 Article in Letonika encyclopedia]\u00a0\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110926210338/http://www.lu.lv/zinas/t/6301/ Exhibition \"Gustavs Vanags and organic chemistry in Latvia]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gudriniece, Emilija}}\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:Latvian chemists]]\n[[Category:Latvian inventors]]\n[[Category:Latvian academicians]]\n[[Category:Academicians of the Latvian SSR Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:University of Latvia alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Latvia faculty]]\n[[Category:Riga Technical University faculty]]\n[[Category:Riga Technical University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Zemgale]]\n[[Category:People from Kovno Governorate]]\n[[Category:People from Auce Municipality]]\n[[Category:20th-century chemists]]\n\n{{cat improve|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Esmu Igors", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCommemoration:wikification", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gustavs_Vanags"}
{"title_page": "I Will Wait", "text_new": "{{About|Mumford & Sons|the song by Hootie & the Blowfish|I Will Wait (Hootie & the Blowfish song)|the song by Swedish artist Isa Tengblad|I Will Wait (Isa song)}}\n{{Distinguish|I Will Wait for You}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Will Wait\n| cover      = I Will Wait single cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Mumford & Sons]]\n| album      = [[Babel (Mumford & Sons album)|Babel]]\n| released   = August 7, 2012\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Phonograph record|7\"]]|[[CD single|CD]]|[[Music download|digital download]]}}\n| recorded   = 2011\u201312\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Indie folk]]|[[folk rock]]|[[bluegrass music|bluegrass]]}}\n| length     = 4:36\n| label      = {{hlist|Gentlemen of the Road|[[Island Records|Island]]}}\n| writer     = [[Marcus Mumford]]\n| producer   = [[Markus Dravs]]\n| chronology = [[Mumford & Sons]]\n| prev_title = [[Roll Away Your Stone]]\n| prev_year  = 2010\n| next_title = [[Lover of the Light]]\n| next_year  = 2012\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = Single\n | cover   = I Will Wait 2.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Promotional artwork\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''I Will Wait'''\" is a song by British [[rock music|rock]] band [[Mumford & Sons]]. The track was first released in the [[United States]] on August 7, 2012 as the [[lead single]] from the band's second studio album, ''[[Babel (Mumford & Sons album)|Babel]]'' (2012).<ref name=\"release\"/> This is their most successful song to date surpassing their biggest hits, \"[[Little Lion Man]]\" and \"[[The Cave (song)|The Cave]]\". It reached the top ten in the [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|New Zealand]], [[Irish Singles Chart|Irish]], [[Canadian Hot 100|Canadian]] and [[Scottish Singles and Albums Charts|Scottish]] national charts, and was voted into fifth place in Australian radio station [[Triple J]]'s [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2012|Hottest 100 of 2012]]. The song is playable in the video game ''[[Guitar Hero Live]]''.\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video was directed by Fred & Nick.<ref>{{cite web | title=I Will Wait {{!}} Mumford & Sons {{!}} Music Video | url=http://www.mtv.com/videos/mumford-sons/834083/i-will-wait.jhtml | work=[[MTV|MTV Music]] | publisher=[[MTV Networks]] | accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> It was filmed at [[Red Rocks Amphitheatre]] in [[Morrison, Colorado|Morrison]], [[Colorado]].\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe song has received generally favourable reviews. Grady Smith of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the song a positive review, saying how the song \"hearkens back to their Grammy-nomination-festooned single \"The Cave\" with its shouted refrain, triumphant horns, a driving kick drum, and an earnest lyric about a relationship so perfect it has Marcus Mumford kneeling down in reverence, raising his hands, and wishing for his mind to be \"freed from the lies.\"\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2012/08/07/mumford-sons-single-i-will-wait|title=Mumford & Sons release new single, 'I Will Wait'|publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=2012-08-07|accessdate=2012-09-09}}</ref> Stephanie Middleton of ''The Celebrity Cafe'' said, \"With untouched vocals and harmonies, the boys manage to create yet another genuine Mumford & Sons track.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thecelebritycafe.com/reviews/2012/08/mumford-sons-i-will-wait-review|title=Mumford & Sons - \"I Will Wait\" - Review|publisher=The Celebrity Cafe|date=2012-08-08|access-date=2012-09-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120813002546/http://thecelebritycafe.com/reviews/2012/08/mumford-sons-i-will-wait-review|archive-date=2012-08-13|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nKatie Hasty of ''[[HitFix]]'' gave the song a B+, saying \"Marcus is a softie, but he's got a problem with repetition,\" but also said \"they bring it home when they jump up an octave and beat the hell out of the chorus.\" She concluded with, \"This song could be really huge.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitfix.com/immaculate-noise/mumford-sons-promise-i-will-wait-in-first-official-song-from-babel-listen|title=Mumford & Sons promise 'I Will Wait' in first official song from 'Babel'|publisher=[[HitFix]]|date=2012-08-08|accessdate=2012-09-09}}</ref> Liv Carter of ''Urban Country News'' awarded the song a 'thumbs-up'. Reviewing the song after it started receiving airplay at country radio, she called it \"a perfect piece of folk-rock that more than deserves to be introduced to the wider country radio audience.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Carter|first=Liv|title=Single Review: 'I Will Wait'&nbsp;\u2013 Mumford & Sons|url=http://www.urbancountrynews.com/single-review-i-will-wait-mumford-sons/|accessdate=27 December 2012|newspaper=Urban Country News}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine named the song the 13th best song of 2012.<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/50-best-songs-of-2012-20121205/mumford-sons-i-will-wait-19691231 50 Best Songs of 2012: Mumford Sons, 'I Will Wait' | Rolling Stone<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Digital download<ref name=\"release\"/>\n| title1 = I Will Wait\n| length1 = 4:36\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = 2013 Brit Awards\n| title1 = I Will Wait (Live from the BRITs)\n| length1 = 4:48\n}}\n\n==Awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Organization !! Award !! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2013 || rowspan=\"2\" | [[55th Annual Grammy Awards|Grammy Award]] || Best Rock Performance || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| Best Rock Song || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| [[2013 MTV Video Music Awards|MTV Video Music Award]] || Best Rock Video || {{Nominated}}\n|}\n\n==Charts==\n===Commercial performance===\nThe song sold 153,000 copies in the United States in its first week of release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/on-the-charts-mumford-sons-fans-cant-wait-for-babel-20120815|title=On the charts: Mumford & Sons' fans can't wait for Babel|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=2012-08-15|accessdate=2012-09-09}}</ref> It is also their highest-charting song both in the US and the UK to date. It has sold over 2 million copies in the US as of April 2013, their second song to do so.<ref name=\"yahoo2013\">{{cite news |url= http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/week-ending-march-31-2013-songs-thrift-shop-201312133.html |title=Week Ending March 31, 2013. Songs: \"Thrift Shop\" Sets First Quarter Record |author=Paul Grein |work=Yahoo Music (Chart Watch)|date=April 3, 2013 |accessdate=April 10, 2013 }}</ref>\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Chart (2012\u201313)\n! Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|23|artist=Mumford & Sons|song=I Will Wait|accessdate=22 December 2014|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|27|artist=Mumford & Sons|song=I Will Wait|accessdate=22 December 2014|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|14|artist=Mumford & Sons|song=I Will Wait|accessdate=22 December 2014|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia Tip|11|artist=Mumford & Sons|song=I Will Wait|accessdate=22 December 2014|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcanadianhot100|9|artist=Mumford & Sons|song=I Will Wait|artistid=311935|accessdate=22 December 2014|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Europe ([[Euro Digital Songs]])<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/chart-search-results/singles/14124057 | publisher = [[Billboard.biz]] | accessdate = September 27, 2012 | title = Chart Search Results&nbsp;\u2013 Euro Digital Songs 2012-10-06}}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|18\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|93|artist=Mumford & Sons|song=I Will Wait|accessdate=22 December 2014|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|53|artist=Mumford & Sons|song=I Will Wait|songid=1053601|accessdate=3 April 2020|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Irish|7|yea